“Equity does not mean that all students obtain equal education outcomes, but rather that differences in students’ outcomes are unrelated to their background or to economic and social circumstances over which students have no control.”



* OECD, 2018



[Online education has become increasingly popular in recent years](https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/education/our-insights/demand-for-online-education-is-growing-are-providers-ready), with more and more learners taking courses remotely to gain educational access. Unfortunately, online education and the technologies used to facilitate it can have significant impacts on equity and inclusion. [Many learners struggle to access the latest digital tools and services](https://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/education/what-makes-students-access-to-digital-learning-more-equitable_e8107345-en), as well as the financial resources and technical literacy necessary for success in online learning environments. This can put disadvantaged learners at a disadvantage and exacerbate existing inequities in education. However, there is also potential for online learning to increase equity and inclusion. 



# Are We Addressing the Core?

The common rhetoric for addressing inequity in digital learning is to ensure equal access to digital tools and services, as well as financial resources and technical literacy. In other words, addressing the digital divide and creating more accessible online learning environments. While this rhetoric isn’t wrong in theory, it does miss something important that’s at the core of ensuring equity in e-learning: assessing the difference between equal learning practices and equity-driven instruction. 



Making learning equitable requires the consideration of diverse perspectives and backgrounds in the design and delivery of learning. Equity-driven learning practices are [rooted in understanding how individual characteristics](https://www.prodigygame.com/main-en/blog/equity-in-the-classroom/#:~:text=Equity%20in%20the%20classroom%20means,Gender) such as race, class, age, gender, identity, sexual orientation and educational status impact how learners obtain and make meaning from their experiences.



This awareness informs equity-driven learning and instructional strategies as they work to ensure that all learners have access to a [high-quality education that promotes equity by addressing systemic inequities](https://crlt.umich.edu/equity-focused-teaching).



## How Should We Define ‘Equitable and Inclusive’ Learning?

Before we dive into defining ‘equitable learning’, let’s take a step back and refresh our understanding of the difference between equality, equity and inclusion. The graphic below may be familiar to you, but it’s a useful visual for an understanding of these concepts:



![](data:image/png;base64,)



The above graphic illustrates the components of an equity-based approach to online learning. At the centre, is the learner, who should be the focus when considering equitable learning strategies. Surrounding the learner are components such as access (to the technology and services required for the course), digital literacy (the ability to effectively navigate digital tools and services) and socioeconomic status (which can influence a learner’s access to the internet and digital devices). Assessing these elements, as well as any potential biases or inequities in the design and delivery of material, will help create equitable and inclusive learning experiences for all.



So, what does the term ‘equal learning practices’ mean? Well, it is often used to describe a set of instructional strategies to ensure that all learners achieve the same standards, but this is not the same as equity-driven learning practices. Equal learning practices are not necessarily equitable; even if they were, they might still fail to achieve equality. 



While there are many definitions of equity-driven learning, [The National Association for Multicultural Education](https://www.nameorg.org/learn/what_is_equity.php#:~:text=Equity%20%2D%2D%20the%20foundation%20for,context%20of%20teaching%20and%20learning.) provides the following useful definition: “Equity – the foundation for multicultural learning – would mean ensuring that every student has access to the curriculum, assessment, pedagogy, and challenge he or she needs based on the recognition of response to individual differences and the sociopolitical context of teaching and learning.”



Despite researchers, scholars and educators differing on the exact definition, there are a few key principles and schools of thought that underpin the thinking behind equity-driven learning. Equity-driven learning refers to an approach where educators and learning designers intentionally design their instructional practices in ways that take into account patterns of privilege and oppression so that all learners can access educational opportunities on an equal playing field. This means addressing issues like racism, sexism, ableism and homophobia — not just making sure each learner meets the same academic goals! While most teachers believe in equality for their learners and want them all to succeed academically (and beyond), equity-driven learning requires a deeper level of reflection about how our work can contribute towards positive social change.



While equity-driven learning practices are about making sure everyone has a fair chance to achieve their goals, it’s important to note that just providing equal opportunities for learners is not enough. For example, there’s a difference between saying, ‘I want my learners to all learn the same things’ and saying, ‘I want them all to have an equal chance of success’. The first implies that we should expect every learner to learn the same material in the same way, whereas the second acknowledges that we need different ways of teaching and different approaches based on each learner’s unique needs.



To sum up: Equity-driven learning is not just about making learning equal; it’s also about giving all learners a fair chance at achieving their goals.



To design for equity requires an understanding of what barriers there are around access or success that could be addressed through our teaching practices. For example: we might recognise that some learners have a difficult time keeping up with the pace of instruction because they work after school; others have trouble accessing digital learning due to a lack of digital access; still others may be struggling with more than one language at home while undertaking digital learning where only English is spoken. 



# Tips for designing equitable and inclusive digital learning strategies

## Identify Inequities and Disparities in Learner Populations



To design equitable and inclusive digital learning strategies, it’s important to identify and address any existing inequities or disparities in learner populations. One way to do this is by gathering data on learners’ backgrounds and access to technology to identify potential gaps or inequalities. This information can be used to tailor learning experiences to meet the needs of all learners, including those from disadvantaged backgrounds. For example, if some learners do not have access to reliable internet or devices at home, educators can provide alternative ways for them to access digital learning resources, such as offering computer labs or loaner devices. Additionally, educators can use this information to design learning experiences that are culturally responsive and inclusive, taking into account the diverse backgrounds and perspectives of learners. By addressing inequities and disparities in learner populations, educators can create digital learning experiences that are accessible and relevant to al learners, regardless of of their socioeconomic status or background.

## Leverage Existing Digital Resources

One way to ensure that all learners have access to the same technologies and services is by leveraging existing digital resources. Educators can identify and use digital resources that are accessible to all learners, regardless of their socioeconomic status. For example, educators can use free or low-cost educational apps or websites that can be accessed from any device with an internet connection. This can help to level the playing field for learners who may not have the same access to technology at home as their peers. By leveraging existing digital resources and providing support for learners who need them, educators can ensure that all learners have equal access to the technologies and services needed for digital learning.



## Assess Technical Literacy Levels

Assessing the technical literacy levels of learners is important to ensure that they have the skills needed to successfully engage in digital learning experiences. Educators can use assessments or surveys to determine learners' technical literacy levels and identify any areas where learners may need additional support. Once learners' technical literacy levels have been assessed, educators can provide appropriate support and training for learners who need it. This can include offering tutorials or workshops on using specific software or tools or providing resources such as user manuals or online guides. Educators can also work with learners to create individualised learning plans that take into account their specific needs and learning styles. By assessing technical literacy levels and providing appropriate support for learners who need it, educators can help to ensure that all learners are able to engage in digital learning experiences to the best of their abilities.



## Measure the Quality of Digital Learning Experiences

Measuring the quality of digital learning experiences is crucial to ensure that learners are engaged and achieving desired learning outcomes. To achieve this, educators can use feedback from learners and educators to evaluate the effectiveness of digital learning experiences. This feedback can be gathered through surveys, quizzes, or other assessments. Based on this feedback, educators can adjust the delivery of content or teaching methods if necessary to improve learning outcomes. Adjustments may include changes to the pacing of the course, increasing or decreasing the number of multimedia used, or altering the assessments used to evaluate learning. Regularly measuring the quality of digital learning experiences and making adjustments as necessary can help to ensure that learners are engaged and achieving desired learning outcomes.



## Consider the Perspectives of Diverse Learners

Creating an inclusive learning environment means acknowledging and valuing the diverse backgrounds and perspectives of all learners. To achieve this, learning experiences must be designed with the perspectives of diverse learners in mind. This can be achieved by incorporating diverse perspectives into learning materials and activities. It is important to make sure that all learners feel represented and that their backgrounds are reflected in the content they engage with. One way to do this is to use culturally responsive teaching strategies that respect and honour the cultural identities of all learners. By incorporating diverse perspectives and using culturally responsive strategies, educators can create learning experiences that are inclusive of all backgrounds and promote equitable outcomes for all learners.



## Invest in Educator Training

Investing in educator training is a critical step to ensure that educators have the necessary skills and knowledge to create equitable and inclusive digital learning experiences. To achieve this, educators should be provided with ongoing training and professional development opportunities to improve their skills. These opportunities can include attending conferences, participating in webinars, or taking online courses. Emphasis should be placed on the importance of cultural awareness and sensitivity in the design and delivery of online learning. Educators should be trained to recognise and address the unique needs of diverse learners, including those from different cultural, linguistic, and socioeconomic backgrounds. Ongoing training can help educators stay up-to-date with emerging technologies and pedagogical practices and ensure that they have the skills and knowledge necessary to create high-quality digital learning experiences for all learners.



## Empower Learners to Stay Engaged

Empowering learners to take charge of their own learning is a critical aspect of effective digital learning strategies. To achieve this, educators should create learning experiences that allow learners to personalise their learning, including the pace and style of instruction. Encouraging self-directed learning through projects and problem-solving exercises can be effective in this regard. Additionally, educators can use strategies like gamification, where elements of game design are applied to learning activities, to keep learners engaged and motivated. Peer-to-peer collaboration is another approach to encourage engagement, allowing learners to work together and learn from one another. Monitoring and assessing the effectiveness of these strategies is important to ensure they are meeting the needs of diverse learners and improving learning outcomes.



# Equitable and Inclusive Strategies to Shape the Present and Future Learning Environment



As we look ahead to the future of education, it’s crucial that we prioritise equity and inclusivity. By creating learning environments that value and support diversity, we can ensure that all learners have equal opportunities to succeed. This requires a multifaceted approach, including providing resources and support for marginalised communities, fostering culturally responsive teaching practices, and challenging systemic inequalities that impact education. By taking action today, we can build a brighter future for all learners, regardless of their backgrounds or circumstances. Let’s work together to create an education system that truly serves everyone.
